  "summary": "At the morgue, Inspector Spence presents the deceased man to Rosaline Claude, claiming the body is Enoch Yates. Rosaline denies ever knowing the man, a reaction that leads Spence to privately suspect she may be a skilled actress. Spence informs David Hunter that Rosaline's testimony should satisfy a jury, though David remains skeptical.\n\nMeanwhile, Hercule Poirot becomes interested in the case after reading a newspaper report regarding the death of Enoch Yates in Wormsley Valley. The report details that the man died from skull fractures and that police are seeking information regarding Yates, who reportedly arrived from Cape Town. Poirot connects the report to a recent visit from Mrs. Leonie Claude and a conversation involving Major Porter.\n\nRowley \"Rolly\" Claude visits Poirot to discuss his late uncle, Gordon Claude, who had married a widow named Andréa Deauville. Rolly suspects that Enoch Yates is actually Robert André using an alias, noting that the name \"Enoch Yates\" is a literary reference to a character who returns to find his wife remarried. Rolly explains that Beatrice Lippincott overheard a conversation suggesting André was in the area under an alias to avoid trouble for David Hunter. He notes the deceased possessed no identification, only personal items like clothing and a toothbrush. Rolly also mentions that David Hunter claimed to have met the man and given him five pounds after receiving a letter stating the man was a friend of the supposedly destitute Robert André.",
